<article id="node-16954">
<h1 >3.4.8.140 Benefits for Partners of RAFS Farmers</h1>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> THIS SCHEME CLOSED on 31 July 2001 and the following INFORMATION is FOR HISTORICAL PURPOSES ONLY.</p>
<h2>Partner pension or benefit</h2>
<p>The partner of a qualifying farmer can apply for any other social security pension or benefit.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> The partner may qualify for <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#pa" title="Partner allowance">PA</a>, <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#pga" title="Parenting allowance">PgA</a> or <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#nsa" title="Newstart allowance">NSA</a>.</p>
</div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 93U Disposal preclusion period-disposals before 1 July 2002, section 23(1)-'social security pension', section 23(1)-'social security benefit'</p>
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../guide-social-security-law/3/2/1">3.2.1</a> NSA - Qualification &amp; Payability, <a href="../guide-social-security-law/3/3/1">3.3.1</a> PA - Qualification &amp; Payability, <a href="../guide-social-security-law/3/5/1">3.5.1</a> PP - Qualification &amp; Payability</p>
</div>
<h2>Backpayment to <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#age" title="Age pension">Age</a> qualified partners</h2>
<p>If the farmer's partner also qualifies for Age, they will receive payment on the same basis as the farmer. That is, if the farmer's pension is backpaid, the partner's pension will also be backpaid.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../guide-social-security-law/3/4/8/120">3.4.8.120</a> Start Day for Payments Accessed via RAFS</p>
</div>
<h2>Backpayment to non age pension age partners</h2>
<p>Partners who have not yet reached age pension age, are entitled to an ex-gratia payment for the same period as their pension age partner. The ex-gratia payment is made as a lump sum.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Explanation:</strong> The ex-gratia payment covers those situations where it may have been difficult for applicants to prove their eligibility for a particular benefit.</p>
</div>
<p>In most cases, the applicant will not be able to provide information to verify that they were qualified throughout the relevant period, particularly if they are claiming NSA.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> It is unlikeIy that a partner who is claiming NSA will be able to prove that they met the activity test requirements during the entire period. However, an applicant would be entitled to an ex-gratia payment for the relevant period if they:</p>
<ul><li>remained working on the farm they had gifted to their eligible descendant, and</li>
<li>now qualified for NSA.</li>
</ul></div>
<p>Where possible, they should still establish that they would have been qualified for the payment during the entire period before an ex-gratia payment can be paid.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> If the partner is claiming <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#pp" title="Parenting payment">PP</a> they will need to establish that they:</p>
<ul><li>were residentially qualified,</li>
<li>had a PP child (<a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/1/p/340">1.1.P.340</a>) at their start date, and</li>
<li>continued to do so until the actual date they lodged the claim.</li>
</ul></div>
<p>In the absence of verification, the applicant should provide a statement regarding their circumstances during the relevant period.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Medical incapacity, residency, employment.</p>
</div>
<p>The partner can be paid the lump sum for any period/s where the delegate is satisfied that the person was qualified.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> If the partner was granted NSA but had been overseas or in full-time employment for 3 months of the relevant period, no payment would be made for those 3 months.</p>
</div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section <span class="nobr">23(5A)</span> Pension age</p>
</div>
<h2>What is included in the ex-gratia payment?</h2>
<p>An ex-gratia payment is not attributed to a particular payment type, but rather an amount equal to what the applicant would have received had they been qualified. This includes any additional payments.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Additional payments would include:</p>
<ul><li>pharmaceutical allowance,</li>
<li>telephone allowance, and</li>
<li>remote area allowance.</li>
</ul></div>
<p>Calculation of the applicant's rate of payment during the ex-gratia period should be based on their income and asset details during the period.</p>
<p>The ex-gratia payment MAY contain a taxable and non-taxable component, depending on the payments it represents. The taxable amount will count as income in the financial year in which it is received.</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> If the partner would have qualified for NSA and <a href="../guide-social-security-law/acronyms#pha" title="Pharmaceutical allowance">PhA</a>, their ex-gratia payment will be assessed as taxable income EXCEPT for the amount in lieu of PhA.</p>
</div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../guide-social-security-law/1/3">1.3</a> Administrative Principles</p>
</div>
